06824nam a22009495i 9780300127805DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001278057 a10.12987/97803001278052doi  a(DE-B1597)485598  a(OCoLC)1024029274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHM131b.R697 1996eb 7aSCI0260002bisacsh04a30722000aRooted in the Land :bEssays on Community and Place /ced. by Wes Jackson, William Vitek. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough contemporary society seems to promote the values of individualism and mobility, this engrossing book is dedicated to the notion that human lives are enriched by participation in a social community that is integrated into the natural landscape of a particular place. The 34 contributors-who include David Ehrenfeld, Lynn R. Miller, Wendell Berry, Deborah Tall, David W. Orr, Robert Swann, and Susan Witt, as well as other philosophers, scientists, activists, economists, historians, farmers and ranchers, sociologists, theologians, and political scientists-offer an array of social and ecological perspectives on the nature of "community." The editors, William Vitek and Wes Jackson, contend that a deeper understanding of communities is critical for the health of the planet and the human spirit. They offer a compelling collection of new and classic writings-many in the form of personal narrative-that extend E. F. Schumacher's ideas about the importance of human scale and Aldo Leopold's concept of biotic citizenship. Proposing eloquent defenses of community life and practical suggestions for becoming connected to others and native to a place, the writers explore the loss of community, the philosophical foundations of communities, and the current renewal of community life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCommunauté. 0aCommunities. 0aCommunity life. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh1 aAustin, Richard Cartwright, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Wendell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrueggemann, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBube, Paul Custodio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, John B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonahue, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrenfeld, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsbjornson, Carl D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlora, Cornelia Butler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlora, Jan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasselstrom, Linda M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrickson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Wes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Wes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalinowski, Franklin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemmis, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKittredge, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKline, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 